<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900905-0061</DOCNO><DOCID>900905-0061.</DOCID><HL>   Yen Futures Trader Pleads   No Contest to Fraud Counts</HL><DATE>09/05/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><IN>COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   CHICAGO -- Martin J. Riley, one of 15 yen futures tradersawaiting trial in federal court here on fraud charges,pleaded no contest to one count of mail and wire fraud andtwo counts of violating the Commodity Exchange Act.   Separately, opening arguments in the trial of the 14 otherdefendants were scheduled for next Tuesday.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Riley's plea before U.S. District Court Judge WilliamHart means that while he isn't contesting the governmentcharges against him in the yen case, his plea can't be usedas an admission of guilt in subsequent civil oradministrative proceedings against him.   Neither Mr. Riley nor his attorney, William Murphy, couldbe reached for comment on the plea.   Many futures traders who have pleaded guilty to fraudcharges stemming from the government's undercoverinvestigation of the futures pits have been fined by thefutures exchanges for admitting to violations of exchangetrading rules.</TEXT></DOC>